s":["Parasympathetic fibres from T10-L2 control penile erection","Pudendal nerve fibres from L1-L3 innervate the bulbospongiosus muscle","Sympathetic fibres from T10-L2 stimulate internal urethral sphincter contraction during emission","Somatic fibres from S2-S4 cause relaxation of the ischiocavernosus muscle","Sympathetic fibres from S2-S4 control ejaculation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe male sexual response involves distinct neural pathways with specific anatomical origins and functions. \u003Cstrong\u003EParasympathetic fibres\u003C/strong\u003E originate from S2-S4 rather than T10-L2 and mediate erection through vasodilation of penile vessels. The \u003Cstrong\u003Epudendal nerve\u003C/strong\u003E arises from S2-S4 rather than L1-L3 and provides somatic innervation to the bulbospongiosus muscle. \u003Cstrong\u003ESomatic fibres\u003C/strong\u003E cause contraction rather than relaxation of the ischiocavernosus muscle during the sexual response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESympathetic fibres from T10-L2 stimulate internal urethral sphincter contraction during emission\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the correct answer. These sympathetic pathways control emission through contraction of the internal urethral sphincter and smooth muscle in the vas deferens. The final option incorrectly attributes sympathetic control of ejaculation to S2-S4 fibres when sympathetic fibres from T10-L2 contribute to emission, while ejaculation involves both sympathetic and somatic pathways.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sympathetic fibres (T10-L2) control emission via internal urethral sphincter contraction","Pudendal nerve (S2-S4) innervates the bulbospongiosus muscle which compresses the urethra during ejaculation","Parasympathetic fibres (S2-S4) mediate erection via vasodilation"],"references":["Dean RC, Lue TF. Physiology of penile erection and pathophysiology of erectile dysfunction. Urol 